org.net4care.skype.appkeypair

Class AppKeyPairMgr

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.net4care.skype.appkeypair.AppKeyPairMgr

  • public class AppKeyPairMgr
extends Object
    Encapsulates validating the pathname and format of the AppKeyPair required to access the SkypeKit runtime.

    However, a valid pathname and format does not guarantee that the AppKeyPair is valid for this application.
    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    Andrea Drane

      • getPemFilePathname

        public String getPemFilePathname()
        Retrieves the fully resolved PEM file path. This reflects the resultant path (valid or invalid) used by the latest invocation of @link{#resolveAppKeyPairPath(String)}, or its default if resolveAppKeyPairPath(String) has not been invoked.
        Returns:
        The the fully resolved PEM file path, which might not be a valid PEM file.
        Since:
        2.0
        See Also:
        KEY_PAIR_DEFAULT_PATHNAME, pemFilePathname

      • resolveAppKeyPairPath

        public boolean resolveAppKeyPairPath()
        Resolves the AppKeyPair X.509 certificate file name based on the configured default pathname of the PEM file containing the actual AppKeyPair data. Sets @link{pemFilePathname} to the resolved name.
        Returns:
        • true: AppKeyPair certificate file exists
        • false:
          • Could not resolve the pathname
          • The specified certificate file does not exist
          pemFilePathname is unchanged.
        Since:
        2.0
        See Also:
        KEY_PAIR_DEFAULT_PATHNAME, resolveAppKeyPairPath(String)

      • resolveAppKeyPairPath

        public boolean resolveAppKeyPairPath(String pathName)
        Common method to resolve the AppKeyPair certificate file name.

        Initially assumes the name of the path of the file containing the AppKeyPair data includes a path component. If it doesn't end in one of the recognized suffixes, assumes its a path-only component and appends the default file pathname KEY_PAIR_DEFAULT_PATHNAME, which it assumes is configured as a filename. Writes diagnostic messages to the console if the specified file does not exist.

        This is useful since SkypeKit currently reports only "TLS handshake failure" (with no further explanation) if the certificate can't be found/accessed or is not validly formatted.
        Parameters:
        pathName - The path of the file containing the actual certificate data.
        Returns:
        • true: AppKeyPair successfully read (and set) from the file data
        • false:
          • Could not open the file
          • Could not read the file
          • Not a valid certificate file
          AppKeyPair is unchanged.
        Since:
        2.0
        See Also:
        KEY_PAIR_FILE_SUFFIXES, KEY_PAIR_DEFAULT_PATHNAME

      • isValidCertificate

        public boolean isValidCertificate()
        Determines whether the current AppKeyPair (as specified by pemFilePathname) is a valid X.509 certificate.

        Writes diagnostic messages to the console if the the current AppKeyPair does not exist or is not valid. This is useful since SkypeKit currently reports only "TLS handshake failure" (with no further explanation) if the certificate can't be found/accessed or is not validly formatted.
        Returns:
        • true: Valid certificate file
        • false:
          • Could not open the file
          • Could not read the file
          • Not a valid certificate file
        Since:
        2.0
        See Also:
        pemFilePathname, org.net4care.skype.api.Net4CareSession.util.MySession#myClientConfiguration
